				<div class="comment-content">
					<p>This piece is about Our Hero&#8217;s reflections on their society&#8217;s belief that wise, angelic people will be coming to them on white ships. They appear to have little evidence that this will happen, or that they will even be wise and angelic.</p>
<p>&gt; His anger marks him in the scant crowds of evening, and our<br />
&gt; calm-moving people glance at him and move aside &#8230;<br />
Great line. I enjoy the how the &#8220;anger marks him&#8221;, and how the sentence sets up an &#8220;us&#8221; vs &#8220;them&#8221; thing. I like the imagery you&#8217;ve used, such as something being as &#8220;inevitable as cream into butter&#8221;.</p>
<p>I was wondering if the angry person is related to the narrator. Specifically, she says that he&#8217;ll return and kiss her cheek, and take up his life. </p>
<p>I also had a problem with the flunging — took me a moment to parse the sentence.</p>
